children.subject: What possible use does 120 brings to a CS-focused person interested in ML? Will this really help me in image processing?
yep seems like a solid schedule. 126/170 look great for your background. 120 is pretty chill and you learn cool stuff
I'm currently enrolled in 170/126. 126 is hands down one of the most useful/applicable courses I've taken at Berkeley and personally I find it to be lower workload than 170.

Some people say that ee126 is a breeze. However, rumors say that the average student taking ee126 got A- and above in both cs70 and cs170. This class is regarded as one of the hardest courses in the EECS department. Usefulness is relevant for ML applications and other specialized applications. If you are comfortable and enjoy probably theory topics and you have refined mathematical maturity then this class is for you.

history.content:
Considering this schedule next semester. Did about 1.7 std dev's above the mean on the probability section of 70, and was a few tenths of a percentage shy of an A+ in 61B, for context. These courses are relevant to my research prospects, hoping someone could weigh in on the workload. I've heard mixed things about 170, with some claiming it's easier than 70 and others saying it's one of the hardest classes they've taken in undergrad. 126 I've heard is a grinder but I like probability/stats a lot and stochastic processes in particular really interest me. I've heard that 120 is generally easy but don't want to underestimate it.

Any help would be appreciated, thanks in advance!
